<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-763-552  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 763 552.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 16 1989 v6 n41 p141(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM's 486 Power Platform is slow to reach dealers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burke, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM Power Platform 486/25 (Circuit board) (marketing).andO;Topic:     Computer industryMarketing StrategyMarket AnalysisDistribution Management.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steven BurkeandM;IBM's announcement two weeks ago that it is shipping the 486/25 PowerPlatform appears to be as much splash as substance.andM;Major retail chains, including those that installed the first PowerPlatforms, last week said they have none in stock and no date from IBM onwhen they can expect another shipment.andM;As a result, salespeople are telling customers they are uncertain when theproduct, which brings the power of the 486 chip to IBM's 386 PS/2 Model 70,will be available.andM;None of the chains were willing to reveal how many 486/25 Power Platformsthey received initially two weeks ago, leaving analysts to suspect thevolumes were extremely small.andM;The 25MHz 486 processor board has a suggested retail price of $3,995 with thetrade-in of a 386 processor.andM;Officials at Valcom Inc., a 181-store chain that installed the first PowerPlatform, said the firm has not received product since the initial shipment.andM;&quot;We don't have a scheduled ship date from IBM right now,&quot; said Geri Michelic,a spokeswoman for Valcom, in Omaha, Neb.andP;  &quot;We're not making any commitmentsto customers until we can get solid facts from IBM.&quot;andM;IBM is shipping the product as fast as it can get the 486 chips from IntelCorp., IBM officials said.andP;  IBM has received several thousand orders for thePower Platform, and demand is expected to exceed supply for some time, theysaid.andM;Linda Dezan, a spokeswoman for IBM in White Plains, N.Y., said the companyhas already shipped hundreds of Power Platforms.andP;  By the end of October, shesaid, IBM expects to begin filling dealers' orders as they were received.andM;Intel will not be able to meet demand for the 486 until the end of the firstquarter next year, said Bill Rash, 486 marketing manager at the Santa Clara,Calif., firm.andP;  He said Intel will more than double the supply from the fourthto first quarter.andO;</TEXT></DOC>